article.description: If there's a more complete player in the NBA than Kevin Garnett, the Chicago Bulls don't want to see him.
article.headline: Garnett hits for 25 points, 15 rebounds, 10 assists
article.linkText: Garnett posts another triple-double in punishing Bulls
article.story:
CHICAGO (AP) -- If there's a more complete player in the NBA than Kevin Garnett, the Chicago Bulls don't want to see him.
Kevin Garnett
Small Forward
Minnesota Timberwolves
Profile
2002-2003 SEASON STATISTICS
GM PPG RPG APG FG% FT%
28 21.5 13.0 5.7 .459 .754
Garnett had his third triple-double of the season Friday night, seeming to be everywhere on the floor as he led the Minnesota Timberwolves to a 113-100 victory over the Bulls. Not only did he have 25 points, 15 rebounds and 10 assists -- all Minnesota highs -- he had three steals and two blocked shots. ''A lot of people talk about who they'd take in their fantasy league or who's the best player. I say there's no question and tonight you saw why,'' said Jalen Rose, whose 22 points led the Bulls. ''He's doing everything other guys are doing, except he's 7 feet tall.'' All five Minnesota starters finished in double figures, with Rasho Nesterovic scoring a season-high 23. Troy Hudson also had 23, Kendall Gill added 17 and Gary Trent had 10 points and 15 rebounds. But it was Garnett who made the difference. ''Someone asked earlier about the best offensive and defensive player and their impact. How about when one player is both?'' Minnesota coach Flip Saunders said. ''He does everything. He can beat you defensively, he can beat you rebounding-wise, he can beat you scoring. ''That's about as complete a game as you can see a guy play.'' Jamal Crawford was one of the few highlights for the Bulls with a career-high 20 points, including seven in a 43-second flurry at the end of the third quarter. The defeat snapped Chicago's four-game home winning streak, its longest in almost five years. ''This was bittersweet,'' said Crawford, who had another run-in with coach Bill Cartwright earlier this week over his lack of playing time. ''I wanted to win.'' That wasn't going to happen, not with Garnett playing the way he did. Minnesota led by as many as 14 in the first half, but the Bulls chipped at the lead until Tyson Chandler's layup made it 62-60 with 8:19 to play in the third. But Minnesota went on a tear, as Garnett hit a 19-footer to ignite a 23-2 run. Garnett and Hudson capped the spurt with back-to-back 3-pointers, giving Minnesota an 85-62 lead with 1:19 left in the third. ''I said, 'It's my fault. I should have been more aggressive out there. Let's go back out there and get them,''' Garnett said of what got the Timberwolves going. ''Our defense started it. We got some turnovers and that led to easy baskets.'' The Bulls called a timeout, and their fans booed as they slowly walked back to the bench. Crawford gave them something to cheer, though, going on his scoring burst when the game resumed. He made a 19-footer, hit a fallaway jumper, snagged the inbounds pass intended for Garnett and then drilled a long 3-pointer. Just like that, Minnesota's lead was down to 85-69. ''High school and college, I guess,'' Crawford said when asked if he's had a run like that. ''I do it in practice sometimes.'' But the rally didn't last long. Gill opened the fourth with two long jumpers, and Hudson made a 3-pointer as Minnesota pushed its lead back to 20. Crawford's 3-pointer with 3:16 to play got the Bulls to 101-90, the closest they'd been since midway through the third. But after a timeout, Gill made a baseline jumper and the Bulls missed their next shot to end their hopes of a comeback. ''We need to find a way to get stops and create a physical presence,'' Rose said. ''You have to get stops and consecutive stops and knock down shots and move the ball, especially against the zone, and we did not do a good job of that.'' Game notes
Minnesota is 9-1 when it scores 100 points or more. ... Rose had a season-high nine rebounds. ... Minnesota has beaten Chicago seven consecutive times, a streak dating to April 3, 1998. ... Minnesota had a season-high 54 rebounds. ... Bulls forward Marcus Fizer, who averaged 15.3 points and 7.5 rebounds off the bench in the previous 10 games, is getting some support for the Sixth Man Award. ''Marcus is a unique player in this league because of his size and ability,'' Cartwright said. ''He's quicker than most forwards and he's bigger than most 3s. He's got an advantage either way.''
